{"id":"2207.05586","submitter":"Minh Tam Pham Nguyen","authors":"Minh Tam, George Thomas, and Dmitry S. Golubev","title":"Photonic heat transport from weak to strong coupling","comments":"8 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.107.104518","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Superconducting circuits provide a favorable platform for quantum\nthermodynamic experiments. An important component for such experiments is a\nheat valve, i.e. a device which allows one to control the heat power flowing\nthrough the system. Here we theoretically study the heat valve based on a\nsuperconducting quantum interference device (SQUID) coupled to two heat baths\nvia two resonators. The heat current in such system can be tuned by magnetic\nflux. We investigate how does the heat current modulation depend on the\ncoupling strength g between the SQUID and the resonators. In the weak coupling\nregime the heat current modulation grows as g2, but, surprisingly, at the\nintermediate coupling it can be strongly suppressed. This effect is linked to\nthe resonant nature of the heat transport at weak coupling, where the heat\ncurrent dependence on the magnetic flux is a periodic set of narrow peaks. At\nthe intermediate coupling, the peaks become broader and overlap, thus reducing\nthe heat modulation. At very strong coupling the heat modulation grows again\nand finally saturates at a constant value.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Jul 2022 15:09:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-12"}
{"id":"2207.05587","submitter":"Alexandre Eremenko","authors":"Alexandre Eremenko, Changfeng Gui, Qinfeng Li, Lu Xu","title":"Rigidity results on Liouville equation","comments":"14 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We give a complete classification of solutions bounded from above of the\nLiouville equation $$-\\Delta u=e^{2u}\\quad\\mbox{in}\\quad {\\mathbf{R}}^2.$$ More\ngenerally, solutions in the class $$N:=\\{ u:\\limsup_{z\\to\\infty}\nu(z)/\\log|z|:=k(u)<\\infty\\}$$ are described. As a consequence, we obtain five\nrigidity results. First, $k(u)$ can take only a discrete set of values: either\n$k=-2$, or $2k$ is a non-negative integer. Second, $u\\to-\\infty$ as\n$z\\to\\infty$, if and only if $u$ is radial about some point. Third, if $u$ is\nsymmetric with respect to $x$ and $y$ axes and $u_x<0,\\; u_y<0$ in the first\nquadrant then $u$ is radially symmetric. Fourth, if $u$ is concave and bounded\nfrom above, then $u$ is one-dimensional. Fifth, if $u$ is bounded from above,\nand the diameter of ${\\mathbf{R}}^2$ with the metric $e^{2u}\\delta$ is $\\pi$,\nwhere $\\delta$ is the Euclidean metric, then $u$ is either radial about a point\nor one-dimensional.\n  In addition, we extend the concavity rigidity result on Liouville equation in\nhigher dimensions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Jul 2022 15:10:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 13 Jul 2022 15:30:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 22 Jul 2022 14:50:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-25"}
